 fetishism and proceeds through what Dussel refers to as the four major drafts of Capital, ultimately situating Marx’s philosophical, economic, ethical, and historical insights in relation to the theological problems of his time. Dussel notes a shift in Marx’s underlying theological schema from a political critique of the state to an economic critique of the commodity fetish as the Devil, or anti-God, of modernity. Marx’s thought, impact, and influence cannot be fully understood without Dussel’s historic reinterpretation of the theological origins and implications of Marx’s critiques of political economy and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFetishism2DLC. 0aFetishism. 0aMetaphorxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aMetaphorxReligious aspects. 0aPhilosophy2DLC. 0aPhilosophy. 0aTheology2DLC. 0aTheology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aDussel, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez-Bustillo, Camilo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027904?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027904/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles